did.unittitle: Records of the Office of Administration and Facilities (Eileen Buckley)
did.abstract: The Records of the Office of Administration and Faciliites, Eileen Buckley contain a wide array of information related to the University's property holdings. Included in the collection are materials that document real estate transactions, plans for future development, and maintence of institutional facilities. The collection spans from 1959-1995.

origination.label: creator
origination.corpname: New York University. Office of Administration and Facilities.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Folders are arranged alphabetically by subject heading then chronologically within each subject heading.
The files are grouped into one series:

odd.head: Physical Access
odd.p: Please note that this collection is stored offsite, and you must contact the repository to schedule access.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: There is no information about materials that are associated by provenance to the described materials that have been physically separated or removed.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The collection consists of financial records, correspondence, project development plans that outline the University's insitutional facilities and its plans for future development. Also included in the collection are contracts between the University and construction companies, budgets for current and future expansion, and reports on the physical condition of NYU buildings.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Eileen Buckley worked for the Office of Administration and Facilities.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Published citations should take the following form: Identification of item, date (if known); Records of the Office of Administration and Facilities (Eileen Buckley); RG 8.0; box number; folder number; New York University Archives, New York University Libraries.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Institutional records of New York University are closed for a period of 20 years from the date of their creation (the date on which each document was written). Board of Trustees records are similarly closed for 35 years from the date of creation. The opening date for files spanning several years will be 20 years from the most recent date. Access will be given to material already 20 years old contained within a collection that is not yet open when such material can be isolated from the rest of the collection.
Materials related to personnel, faculty grievances, job searches and all files included in the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) are permanently restricted.
